revision.text:
{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Animal, Vegetable, Miracle | title_orig = | translator = | image = Animal Vegetable Miracle.jpg | caption = US hardback cover | author = [[Barbara Kingsolver]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = Food, [[Industrial agriculture]], [[Organic food]], [[Cooking]], [[Memoir]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[HarperCollins]] | pub_date = May 1, 2007 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print (Paperback) | pages = 384 pp | isbn = 978-0-06-085255-9 | dewey= 641.0973 22 | congress= S521.5.A67 K56 2007 | oclc= 77573806 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Animal, Vegetable, Miracle: A Year of Food Life''''' (2007) is a non-fiction book by [[Barbara Kingsolver]] detailing her family's attempt to eat only locally grown food for an entire year.
==Description== The book revolves around the concept of improving the family's diet by eating only foods that her family was able to grow themselves or obtain locally (save for grains and [[olive oil]]). Kingsolver, along with her husband and daughters, start a farm in [[Virginia]] where they grow and [[canning|can]] different varieties of tomatoes, learn about rooster [[husbandry]], make cheese, and adjust to eating foods only when they are locally in season. The book contrasts this with the ecological costs of growing food in [[factory farm]]s, transporting it thousands of miles, and adding chemical [[preservatives]] so it will not spoil.<ref name="csm">{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2007/0508/p13s02-bogn.html|title=A Year of Eating Locally in 'Animal, Vegetable, Miracle'|last=Kehe|first=Marjorie|date=May 8, 2007|publisher=Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=2009-09-05}}</ref><ref name="globe">{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2007/05/20/the_constant_gardener/|title=The Constant Gardener|last=Bass|first=Rick|date=May 20, 2007|publisher=Boston Globe|accessdate=2009-09-05}}</ref>
An excerpt was published in the May/June 2007 issue of ''[[Mother Jones magazine|Mother Jones]]'' magazine, and is available online.<ref>[https://www.motherjones.com/news/feature/2007/05/seeing_red.html Excerpt of ''Animal, Vegetable, Miracle: A Year of Food Life'' at motherjones.com]</ref> There are also audio files of a May 16, 2007 discussion between Kingsolver and her husband at an hour-long presentation at a bookstore in [[Corte Madera, California]].<ref>{{cite web|date=May 16, 2007 |title=Barbara Kingsolver's "Animal, Vegetable, Miracle" |url=http://globalpublicmedia.com/barbara_kingsolvers_animal_vegetable_miracle |publisher=Global Public Media |accessdate=2009-09-05}}</ref>
==Critical reception== ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Lev Grossman named it one of the Top 10 Nonfiction Books of 2007, ranking it at #7.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/top10/article/0,30583,1686204_1686244_1691789,00.html Grossman, Lev; Top 10 Nonfiction Books; time.com]</ref> Rick Bass wrote in ''The Boston Globe'' that "this text will fold quietly into the reader's consciousness, with affecting grace and dignity, because of its prose and sensibilities."<ref name="globe"/> and that "Kingsolver is no pious soapboxer, but instead explores these ideas with enthusiasm and the awe of discovery."<ref name="globe"/>
